00:16:11.680 --> 00:16:13.680
So where was this now, this was in?

00:16:13.680 --> 00:16:29.680
Lotteries. But what I say is, and I'd always been saying this, you don't know, there's 500 of them and you might know individuals, few individuals throughout the factory

00:16:29.680 --> 00:16:38.680
and you know a lot by sight because you don't really know them. But you see them often enough to know that they're part of the factory workers.

00:16:38.680 --> 00:16:47.680
But because you're one of a few, they'll know every single thing about your business. And they think they know you.

00:16:47.680 --> 00:16:55.680
So when they meet you out, they'll greet you like an old friend thinking that you know just as much about them as they know about you.

00:16:55.680 --> 00:17:05.680
But you don't, you see. They're just a face in a crowd. And you only get to know the ones that you were immediately working with.

00:17:05.680 --> 00:17:20.680
Like I knew all of my team that I had, my candle-wick machinists. But it's very rarely, and you have individual friends, that's why you'd be waving across the factory.

00:17:20.680 --> 00:17:32.680
Because your friend would be working in a different thing on the other side of the factory. And you all learned to live with so you could talk to them over the noise and over the distance that you were away.

00:17:32.680 --> 00:17:38.680
Did you find that difficult then that you'd been separated from your friends?

00:17:39.680 --> 00:17:50.680
No, not really, no. I was conscious of it. Perhaps somebody else wouldn't have been conscious of it. But I was conscious that it had made a difference.

00:17:50.680 --> 00:18:00.680
And did you mind that as you were saying, everybody knew who you were, and everybody thought they knew your business. Did you mind that?

00:18:00.680 --> 00:18:13.680
No, no, because it's inevitable. You were of interest to them. They all want to think that they know you, because you were in a superior position.

00:18:13.680 --> 00:18:27.680
So they talk about you, either good or bad. They probably hate your guts. But they wanted to know you, so they want to know all about you.

00:18:27.680 --> 00:18:32.680
It's a strange phenomenon.

00:18:32.680 --> 00:18:42.680
Would there be a lot of gossiping going on then in the factory? About the people working there?

00:18:42.680 --> 00:18:52.680
Yes. What women are, some of it is quite catty. But it depends on you. If you are catty, then you can belong to this catty group.

00:18:52.680 --> 00:19:06.680
But if you're not, they don't come into your area, because you have nothing to do with them. Even in a factory, the type of person you'd want to be friends with,

00:19:06.680 --> 00:19:15.680
you wouldn't be friends with the ones you wouldn't be friends with in any circumstances, because they're not your sort. You've got nothing in common.

00:19:15.680 --> 00:19:18.680
But aren't you friends with the people who are sitting next to you?

00:19:18.680 --> 00:19:19.680
Yes, oh yes.

00:19:19.680 --> 00:19:21.680
Just because of circumstances?

00:19:21.680 --> 00:19:33.680
Yes, because of circumstances. But then they might be talking about other people outside your group. But you don't have to belong to that, do you?

00:19:33.680 --> 00:19:35.680
No, you don't have to take part.

00:19:35.680 --> 00:19:44.680
So you don't have to take part. So they know it would be no good talking to you about other people, because you weren't interested.

00:19:44.680 --> 00:19:54.680
Was a supervisor's job something that was coveted then? Because you know it gave you privileges like the toilet.

00:19:54.680 --> 00:19:56.680
No, I don't think it was.

00:19:56.680 --> 00:20:01.680
Some people do well with responsibility, but some don't, do they?

00:20:01.680 --> 00:20:15.680
What I found, when I worked in the hospital, I was always trying to find supervisors, and it's no good advertising and bringing somebody in from outside. It doesn't work.

00:20:15.680 --> 00:20:18.680
Why not?

00:20:18.680 --> 00:20:29.680
Well, when they don't know the setup, they don't know the hospital, they've got to have someone to teach them from scratch. It's not what you want with a supervisor.

00:20:29.680 --> 00:20:42.680
They're not useful to you. But to try and get some of the girls who you knew would do well to take on the responsibility was hard.

00:20:42.680 --> 00:20:57.680
Because that big step over the threshold of being one of the girls and being in management is, you know, some of them didn't want to take it. They didn't want it. They wanted to be with the girls.

00:20:57.680 --> 00:21:11.680
So I instigated a system where there was a couple of girls who were really good, I had, when I worked in the hospital, and they wouldn't take on a supervisor's role.

00:21:11.680 --> 00:21:24.680
So in the end I said to the one girl, she's done really well for herself now, why don't you take it on temporarily and give it a try?

00:21:24.680 --> 00:21:35.680
I said, you can work with Margaret and she'll show you the ropes. This is one of my supervisors. So she did that for a day and I thought, well that's not really working.

00:21:35.680 --> 00:21:48.680
So because they didn't, the girls didn't respect that she was now supervising. So I ordered some more overalls and I gave her a supervisor's overall.

00:21:48.680 --> 00:22:01.680
And I said, when you do your supervising duties, you have to wear a supervisor's uniform so that all the girls know that you're no longer one of them.

00:22:01.680 --> 00:22:13.680
You are a supervisor and you have other responsibilities. So she gave it a go so that when the vacancy came, I had a trained supervisor ready to step in.

00:22:13.680 --> 00:22:24.680
Because she took the job then, because she knew what it entailed and she wasn't afraid of it anymore and she'd sorted out a relationship with the rest of the girls.

00:22:24.680 --> 00:22:42.680
So it wasn't a big transition from one role to the other. And when she left me, she went into, when they went out to tender in the hospital, she went in, she came to see me and said that she was going to apply.

00:22:42.680 --> 00:22:54.680
That she was going to apply for this job on the monitoring side of the new contract. And I said, go for it. There was a lot more money than she had.

00:22:54.680 --> 00:23:01.680
Because what I said to her in the beginning was, you don't always want to be a cleaner. There's more to life than cleaners.

00:23:01.680 --> 00:23:03.680
But there's nothing wrong with that, is there?

00:23:03.680 --> 00:23:09.680
Oh no, but the money aspect of it, she was only getting paid a cleaner's money.

00:23:09.680 --> 00:23:20.680
And if she had the chance to go on and increase her earnings, the whole family benefited, didn't they? Her husband, the kids.

00:23:20.680 --> 00:23:26.680
I said, you want to look at it like that, you have to look at what you're getting for going out every day.

00:23:26.680 --> 00:23:32.680
But do you think that lack of, well ambition's probably not the right word, but lack of confidence then.

00:23:32.680 --> 00:23:37.680
Yeah, lack of confidence and really lack of ambition because they don't think they can do it.

00:23:37.680 --> 00:23:46.680
She was a brilliant supervisor and she's gone on, she's got quite a high position in the hospital now from this monitoring job.

00:23:46.680 --> 00:23:54.680
You know, I often think, if I hadn't pushed you, you would never have started. She didn't know she could do it.

00:23:55.680 --> 00:24:11.680
And there was a couple of others who I pushed in the same way because some women got no ambition and they don't look at the far distance thing with money.

00:24:11.680 --> 00:24:16.680
If you can increase your earnings, that's what you should be trying to do.

00:24:16.680 --> 00:24:26.680
But it might be that lack of confidence though, do you think? Because perhaps it's the way they've been brought up, that they haven't been told that they can do stuff.

00:24:26.680 --> 00:24:28.680
Yeah, it's lack of confidence.

00:24:28.680 --> 00:24:37.680
Do you feel that you were respected when you were a supervisor? Because you were a production manager as well, weren't you?

00:24:37.680 --> 00:24:42.680
Well, as much as you can do, they don't like you because you tell them what to do.

00:24:42.680 --> 00:24:47.680
You know, you're always being popular, you can be popular and then popular.

00:24:50.680 --> 00:25:03.680
If you always get things done, if you do your job, that's the thing, if you do what you're paid for, they're going to always want you to do beyond their side.

00:25:03.680 --> 00:25:06.680
You know, how can I explain?

00:25:06.680 --> 00:25:08.680
The management you mean?

00:25:08.680 --> 00:25:09.680
No, the girls.

00:25:09.680 --> 00:25:12.680
Because you've got to control these girls, haven't you?

00:25:12.680 --> 00:25:19.680
It's a peculiar relationship you've got with the people who work for you.

00:25:19.680 --> 00:25:24.680
You've got to be able to make them do what you want without any hassle.

00:25:24.680 --> 00:25:33.680
And if you say, do it, they're going to do it because they know that you're not taking advantage of them and you're not bossing them around.

00:25:33.680 --> 00:25:37.680
They've just got to do it because you've told them they've got to do it.

00:25:37.680 --> 00:25:39.680
It's a difficult relationship.

00:25:39.680 --> 00:25:46.680
But did you feel like piggy in the middle a bit then, because you were trying to fulfil what the management wanted as well?

00:25:46.680 --> 00:25:49.680
No, I never felt that with the girls.

00:25:49.680 --> 00:25:57.680
I did feel that sometimes with fellow supervisors.

00:25:57.680 --> 00:26:00.680
Sometimes there was a lot of bitchiness.

00:26:00.680 --> 00:26:08.680
When I first took supervisor, there was a lot of resentment about it from other supervisors.

00:26:08.680 --> 00:26:09.680
Why though?

00:26:09.680 --> 00:26:11.680
I don't know why, but they didn't like it.

00:26:11.680 --> 00:26:13.680
Perhaps they felt threatened or something?

00:26:13.680 --> 00:26:17.680
I don't know, they just didn't like it.

00:26:17.680 --> 00:26:27.680
And there was one or two that were really helpful, but there was one or two that you had to watch because they would be after your blood really.

00:26:27.680 --> 00:26:31.680
But in what way would that manifest itself?

00:26:31.680 --> 00:26:33.680
Would they be talking about you?

00:26:33.680 --> 00:26:37.680
No, they would tell you wrong information.

00:26:37.680 --> 00:26:39.680
That's fairly sneaky.

00:26:39.680 --> 00:26:40.680
It is, yeah.

00:26:40.680 --> 00:26:41.680
That's what I found.

00:26:41.680 --> 00:26:45.680
But then if I went to one of the others and said, you know, what about that?

00:26:45.680 --> 00:26:48.680
They'd say, oh no, no, don't do that.

00:26:48.680 --> 00:26:52.680
And so there was people who were helpful and people who weren't.

00:26:53.680 --> 00:26:58.680
And it was always amazing which ones turned out to be helpful to you.

00:26:58.680 --> 00:27:00.680
Oh right, well that's interesting.

00:27:00.680 --> 00:27:03.680
Not who you would necessarily have predicted then.

00:27:03.680 --> 00:27:05.680
Yeah, predicted, yeah.

