Because if you worked on a sugar plantation and you were a slave,

00:33:36.680 --> 00:33:38.680
you were a commodity.

00:33:38.680 --> 00:33:45.680
So they might have beaten you up and treated you rotten,

00:33:45.680 --> 00:33:53.680
but you did get fed and you did get clothing and you did have somewhere to sleep.

00:33:53.680 --> 00:34:00.680
Well, in this country, during the same period, people didn't get that.

00:34:00.680 --> 00:34:06.680
They didn't get a decent wage, they didn't get clothes, they didn't get food.

00:34:06.680 --> 00:34:12.680
And if they hented on the lordships' land for rabbits, they'd probably get...

00:34:12.680 --> 00:34:13.680
Shipped off.

00:34:13.680 --> 00:34:14.680
Yeah, shipped off, yeah.

00:34:14.680 --> 00:34:20.680
So he reckoned this guy, that the British public, the British people,

00:34:20.680 --> 00:34:23.680
were the most enslaved nation in the world.

00:34:23.680 --> 00:34:27.680
And it's the same today, we really are slaves.

00:34:27.680 --> 00:34:28.680
Yeah.

00:34:28.680 --> 00:34:32.680
My father always used to say, because he was a miner,

00:34:32.680 --> 00:34:35.680
although he had different views to all the other miners,

00:34:35.680 --> 00:34:40.680
he was very individual, but he used to say that the horses were looked after better than the workers.

00:34:40.680 --> 00:34:41.680
Yeah, I bet, yeah.

00:34:41.680 --> 00:34:43.680
Because they were worth more, weren't they?

00:34:43.680 --> 00:34:44.680
Oh yeah, yeah.

00:34:44.680 --> 00:34:47.680
Well, he's always another worker, a lot.

00:34:47.680 --> 00:34:49.680
You have to go and look for a horse.

00:34:49.680 --> 00:34:51.680
You know, it's a fact.

00:34:51.680 --> 00:34:54.680
And that's what this boy's thesis was about.

00:34:54.680 --> 00:34:59.680
When he was talking about it, I thought, yes, you're absolutely right.

00:34:59.680 --> 00:35:01.680
You know, you are right.

00:35:01.680 --> 00:35:09.680
I think they've got a much more relaxed attitude to work on the continent even, haven't they, than here.

00:35:09.680 --> 00:35:15.680
You know, there's more of an exploitative element in this country, perhaps.

00:35:15.680 --> 00:35:18.680
It's the establishment.

00:35:19.680 --> 00:35:24.680
If we didn't have the establishment, we would be all right as a nation.

00:35:24.680 --> 00:35:27.680
I don't think that's going to change very soon.

00:35:27.680 --> 00:35:30.680
No, because the thing is, they're getting poorer, that's the only thing.

00:35:30.680 --> 00:35:34.680
Some of them are getting richer, but the majority of them are getting more.

00:35:34.680 --> 00:35:38.680
The old lot, the old lot that...

00:35:38.680 --> 00:35:39.680
Old money.

00:35:39.680 --> 00:35:43.680
Yeah, old money is getting tighter, but the new money is just...

00:35:43.680 --> 00:35:44.680
Yeah, on the up.

00:35:44.680 --> 00:35:45.680
On the up, yeah.

00:35:45.680 --> 00:35:51.680
Was there anybody that you admired, either in lotteries or in RSW, anybody you looked up to?

00:35:52.680 --> 00:35:56.680
Well, I know he was a rogue, but I quite liked Harry Nash.

00:36:00.680 --> 00:36:02.680
Yes, I worked with another guy.

00:36:05.680 --> 00:36:08.680
An Irish guy, an Irish name.

00:36:08.680 --> 00:36:11.680
He was lovely.

00:36:11.680 --> 00:36:12.680
I worked a lot with him.

00:36:12.680 --> 00:36:13.680
I worked a lot with him.

00:36:13.680 --> 00:36:16.680
I was working for him when I started, you know.

00:36:16.680 --> 00:36:19.680
So why did you admire him, for example?

00:36:19.680 --> 00:36:21.680
Because he was always helpful.

00:36:21.680 --> 00:36:22.680
Right.

00:36:22.680 --> 00:36:26.680
He would explain things and he'd be helpful.

00:36:26.680 --> 00:36:30.680
And he didn't have a blame...

00:36:30.680 --> 00:36:33.680
He wasn't part of the blame culture.

00:36:33.680 --> 00:36:39.680
The majority of people have got to have someone who they can blame when things go wrong.

00:36:39.680 --> 00:36:40.680
Yes, very true.

00:36:40.680 --> 00:36:42.680
It's a blame culture.

00:36:42.680 --> 00:36:44.680
There's nobody to blame.

00:36:44.680 --> 00:36:46.680
Not even you, when you're in the middle of it.

00:36:46.680 --> 00:36:49.680
It's just a fact that it happens.

00:36:49.680 --> 00:36:51.680
Things can go wrong.

00:36:51.680 --> 00:36:53.680
That's very prevalent now, though, isn't it, blame culture?

00:36:53.680 --> 00:36:54.680
Oh, yeah, yeah.

00:36:54.680 --> 00:36:57.680
More so now, I think, than back then.

00:36:57.680 --> 00:36:58.680
Yeah.

00:36:58.680 --> 00:37:09.680
But with, you know, health and safety, for example, if you've left something on the floor and you fall over it, it's the fault of the factory.

00:37:09.680 --> 00:37:13.680
It's not your fault for leaving it there, whereas perhaps years ago you'd be told,

00:37:13.680 --> 00:37:15.680
you shouldn't have put it there then, should you?

00:37:15.680 --> 00:37:17.680
Or whatever.

00:37:17.680 --> 00:37:20.680
But there's more people out to make money.

00:37:20.680 --> 00:37:22.680
They think they're going to make some money.

00:37:22.680 --> 00:37:29.680
If they fall down, they go to litigation because they're out after the money.

00:37:29.680 --> 00:37:35.680
People are a lot more conscious of being able to...

00:37:35.680 --> 00:37:36.680
Yeah, they're clued up.

00:37:36.680 --> 00:37:37.680
Yeah.

00:37:37.680 --> 00:37:40.680
They want to get the money.

00:37:40.680 --> 00:37:44.680
So they want to blame somebody so that they can say,

00:37:44.680 --> 00:37:47.680
that's your fault and you've got to pay me some money.

00:37:47.680 --> 00:37:51.680
Was there any accidents that you remember?

00:37:51.680 --> 00:37:55.680
Did I ask you this last time?

00:37:55.680 --> 00:37:56.680
I can't remember.

00:37:56.680 --> 00:37:57.680
Needles in fingers.

00:37:57.680 --> 00:37:58.680
Oh, yes, yes.

00:37:58.680 --> 00:38:00.680
But they would take you to the hospital.

00:38:00.680 --> 00:38:02.680
They sent you to the hospital.

00:38:02.680 --> 00:38:04.680
Did that happen to you?

00:38:04.680 --> 00:38:08.680
I've seen him several times.

00:38:08.680 --> 00:38:11.680
Yes, and I did once fall over.

00:38:11.680 --> 00:38:17.680
They had a doctor that used to come in and examine all new.

00:38:17.680 --> 00:38:20.680
If you had to watch him, he was a bit...

00:38:20.680 --> 00:38:24.680
You know, today, when I see these things about Russ...

00:38:24.680 --> 00:38:25.680
Rob Harris?

00:38:25.680 --> 00:38:30.680
Rob Harris and all these others, I think you didn't know what we had to go through.

00:38:30.680 --> 00:38:32.680
So what do you mind asking?

00:38:32.680 --> 00:38:33.680
Sorry, I shouldn't laugh, really.

00:38:33.680 --> 00:38:35.680
So what would he do?

00:38:35.680 --> 00:38:38.680
He'd always have to strip to the waist.

00:38:38.680 --> 00:38:41.680
And if you wouldn't take your bra off, he would go...

00:38:43.680 --> 00:38:44.680
Ping it?

00:38:44.680 --> 00:38:46.680
Yes, ping your bra.

00:38:46.680 --> 00:38:49.680
Why would you need to do that?

00:38:49.680 --> 00:38:50.680
That was him.

00:38:50.680 --> 00:38:54.680
He used to enjoy his job, he did.

00:38:54.680 --> 00:38:56.680
Everybody told...

00:38:56.680 --> 00:38:58.680
All the girls went on about it.

00:38:58.680 --> 00:39:00.680
They'd go, oh, I've got to go and see this.

00:39:00.680 --> 00:39:01.680
I can't remember what his name was.

00:39:01.680 --> 00:39:03.680
That's just as well, really.

00:39:03.680 --> 00:39:06.680
But it was a laugh.

00:39:06.680 --> 00:39:08.680
Everybody had suffered.

00:39:08.680 --> 00:39:10.680
That's just how it was.

00:39:10.680 --> 00:39:12.680
Somebody told him, well, literally.

00:39:12.680 --> 00:39:15.680
Nobody had complained either.

00:39:15.680 --> 00:39:18.680
I don't think they did.

00:39:18.680 --> 00:39:20.680
He was a fact of life, you know.

00:39:20.680 --> 00:39:25.680
You had to go and have this medical, and he was the doctor that did the medical examination.

00:39:25.680 --> 00:39:27.680
And that's the way he was, you know.

00:39:27.680 --> 00:39:29.680
He'd touch you up.

00:39:29.680 --> 00:39:31.680
So you didn't take any notice.

00:39:31.680 --> 00:39:34.680
It was an odd deal by...

00:39:35.680 --> 00:39:38.680
You didn't have a nickname for him, did you?

00:39:38.680 --> 00:39:40.680
No, I don't think they did.

00:39:40.680 --> 00:39:42.680
They'd say, oh, God.

00:39:42.680 --> 00:39:44.680
Especially if you were ordered to go for some reason or other.

00:39:44.680 --> 00:39:46.680
You had a rash or anything.

00:39:46.680 --> 00:39:49.680
You'd still have to take your bra off.

00:39:49.680 --> 00:39:51.680
Strip to the waist.

00:39:53.680 --> 00:39:56.680
But it was just a fact of life.

00:39:56.680 --> 00:39:58.680
I think that you had a lot...

00:39:58.680 --> 00:40:01.680
But would he actually touch somebody or just have a look?

00:40:01.680 --> 00:40:03.680
Yeah, have a look.

00:40:04.680 --> 00:40:06.680
That wouldn't happen today, would it?

00:40:06.680 --> 00:40:08.680
No, he'd be sued.

00:40:08.680 --> 00:40:10.680
Have a kill.

00:40:10.680 --> 00:40:12.680
That's what I think they'd say.

00:40:12.680 --> 00:40:17.680
He sexually harassed them.

00:40:17.680 --> 00:40:19.680
Or, you know...

00:40:20.680 --> 00:40:23.680
I think to myself, you kept out of his way.

00:40:23.680 --> 00:40:26.680
You never voluntarily went to see this man.

00:40:26.680 --> 00:40:28.680
Only if you were ordered.

00:40:29.680 --> 00:40:34.680
So a lot of that on theirs is a similar type of thing.

00:40:34.680 --> 00:40:37.680
Why didn't they just keep out of his way?

00:40:40.680 --> 00:40:42.680
How often was he in the factory?

00:40:42.680 --> 00:40:44.680
He wasn't there full-time. He counted.

00:40:44.680 --> 00:40:48.680
No, he'd come sort of once a month.

00:40:48.680 --> 00:40:50.680
He'd be in with the nurse.

00:40:50.680 --> 00:40:53.680
You'd always have the nurse there, mind.

00:40:53.680 --> 00:40:57.680
So what would he be like if he didn't have the nurse?

00:41:00.680 --> 00:41:02.680
It was just a fact of life.

00:41:02.680 --> 00:41:07.680
So if you were ordered to go and see the doctor, it would be about a rash or something?

00:41:07.680 --> 00:41:11.680
Or something, because you get dermatitis in...

00:41:12.680 --> 00:41:14.680
Oh, do you? In factories?

00:41:14.680 --> 00:41:16.680
With cloth.

00:41:16.680 --> 00:41:19.680
Because you get mites that live in the cloth.

00:41:19.680 --> 00:41:21.680
Oh!

00:41:21.680 --> 00:41:27.680
You know, it's like a mite that is living in the cloth.

00:41:27.680 --> 00:41:28.680
In wool?

00:41:28.680 --> 00:41:30.680
All sorts of things, yes.

00:41:30.680 --> 00:41:32.680
Oh, right. I hadn't realised that.

00:41:32.680 --> 00:41:36.680
You get bitten by... they're almost invisible. You can't see them.

00:41:36.680 --> 00:41:38.680
So who would notice that then?

00:41:38.680 --> 00:41:41.680
Well, you would if you were itching, because you're itching.

00:41:41.680 --> 00:41:44.680
You wouldn't admit to that if you had to go and see him, would you?

00:41:45.680 --> 00:41:49.680
You didn't have any folk remedies or anything like that to sort it out yourselves?

00:41:49.680 --> 00:41:53.680
No, no. But it was something that could happen.

00:41:53.680 --> 00:41:56.680
It might not be anything. It might not have been dermatitis.

00:41:56.680 --> 00:41:58.680
But you have to be careful.

00:41:58.680 --> 00:42:02.680
You know, because you can become allergic to the cloth.

00:42:02.680 --> 00:42:04.680
Oh, right.

00:42:04.680 --> 00:42:09.680
And sometimes there's chemicals in it that come out when it's steamed.

00:42:09.680 --> 00:42:12.680
So that would affect the pressers then, would it?

00:42:12.680 --> 00:42:17.680
Pressers would have problems. They'd have respiratory problems.

00:42:17.680 --> 00:42:19.680
Oh, gosh.

00:42:19.680 --> 00:42:21.680
It was...

00:42:21.680 --> 00:42:23.680
Dangerous work.

00:42:23.680 --> 00:42:26.680
It could be, if you were particularly sensitive.

00:42:26.680 --> 00:42:30.680
Yeah. Did some girls ever finish there due to health problems?

00:42:30.680 --> 00:42:32.680
I never heard of anybody.

00:42:32.680 --> 00:42:35.680
But there was always a big turnover of females.

00:42:35.680 --> 00:42:38.680
Why is that then? Because it was so difficult?

00:42:38.680 --> 00:42:41.680
No, they just... their jobs were so easy to come by.

00:42:41.680 --> 00:42:43.680
They'd get another job and move on.

00:42:43.680 --> 00:42:46.680
But what type of job would they get instead of working there?

00:42:46.680 --> 00:42:51.680
Well, in Newport there was Santons that were totally different.

00:42:51.680 --> 00:42:53.680
They made water heaters.

00:42:53.680 --> 00:42:56.680
But would that work later then?

00:42:56.680 --> 00:43:01.680
I don't think so. It was still the same boring old repetitive stuff.

00:43:01.680 --> 00:43:05.680
You know, and there were standard telephones.

00:43:05.680 --> 00:43:08.680
Now, standard telephones was a much better job.

00:43:08.680 --> 00:43:11.680
You were at market if you worked for standard telephones.

00:43:11.680 --> 00:43:13.680
Why, though?

00:43:13.680 --> 00:43:15.680
I don't know. It's all part of the snobbery.

00:43:15.680 --> 00:43:17.680
Was the money better?

00:43:17.680 --> 00:43:19.680
I don't think so.

00:43:19.680 --> 00:43:22.680
Better money doesn't necessarily reflect status, though, does it, with work?

00:43:22.680 --> 00:43:25.680
No, but the thing is, if you'd worked...

00:43:25.680 --> 00:43:28.680
A couple of my friends worked at standard telephones,

00:43:28.680 --> 00:43:33.680
and I don't honestly know what they do, what they were doing.

00:43:33.680 --> 00:43:38.680
But I think they thought they were educationally a bit better.

00:43:38.680 --> 00:43:42.680
You know, you can't tell with women.

00:43:42.680 --> 00:43:47.680
It's strange. It's become a fact.

00:43:47.680 --> 00:43:51.680
But if you worked in the clothing factory,

00:43:51.680 --> 00:43:54.680
it was something you had for the rest of your life.

00:43:54.680 --> 00:44:01.680
You would learn something which was useful and pertinent to the rest of your life.

00:44:01.680 --> 00:44:04.680
If you were good at learning,

00:44:04.680 --> 00:44:08.680
because it wasn't just piecework and repetitive stuff,

00:44:08.680 --> 00:44:11.680
you could make garments for yourself.

00:44:11.680 --> 00:44:14.680
You could make garments for your children.

00:44:14.680 --> 00:44:17.680
I used to make suits for my ex-husband,

00:44:17.680 --> 00:44:20.680
because I knew how to do it.

00:44:20.680 --> 00:44:24.680
Is it because you worked in a particular type of clothing factory?

00:44:24.680 --> 00:44:26.680
Yeah, because it was a uniformed tanner.

00:44:26.680 --> 00:44:30.680
It wasn't just sewing parts of blouses.

00:44:30.680 --> 00:44:34.680
Because that wouldn't necessarily have given you those skills, would it?

00:44:34.680 --> 00:44:39.680
No, no, but you still have learned something that's useful.

00:44:39.680 --> 00:44:41.680
Because if you can use a sewing machine,

00:44:41.680 --> 00:44:45.680
you can use your sewing machine in your home life, can't you?

00:44:45.680 --> 00:44:51.680
And then when you get to 60 and you've retired, you can become a quilter.

00:44:51.680 --> 00:44:56.680
Can you remember any rules and regulations then?

00:44:57.680 --> 00:45:01.680
For example, were there any sacrible offences?

00:45:04.680 --> 00:45:06.680
I'm sure there must have been.

00:45:06.680 --> 00:45:17.680
But if you're not sort of bolshy and causing trouble and causing fights.

00:45:17.680 --> 00:45:21.680
I mean, there used to be trouble, especially over fellers.

00:45:21.680 --> 00:45:24.680
They would fight over fellers.

00:45:24.680 --> 00:45:26.680
Physically, obviously.

00:45:26.680 --> 00:45:28.680
Physically, some of them.

00:45:28.680 --> 00:45:31.680
Do you remember seeing anybody fighting?

00:45:31.680 --> 00:45:35.680
I think once, when she was over a man.

00:45:35.680 --> 00:45:37.680
On the factory floor?

00:45:37.680 --> 00:45:39.680
No, it was something out of work.

00:45:39.680 --> 00:45:43.680
All right. But where were they fighting in the factory?

00:45:43.680 --> 00:45:45.680
In the toilets.

00:45:45.680 --> 00:45:47.680
Oh gosh.

00:45:47.680 --> 00:45:49.680
In the toilet area, you know, in the cloakroom.

00:45:49.680 --> 00:45:51.680
Yeah, yeah.

00:45:51.680 --> 00:45:57.680
But you'd have had to have been sort of interested in that.

00:45:57.680 --> 00:46:02.680
I mean, I did know that it was going on and everybody was going down to have a look,

00:46:02.680 --> 00:46:05.680
but I was more interested in money.

00:46:05.680 --> 00:46:08.680
Who would have stopped it then? Supervisors?

00:46:08.680 --> 00:46:10.680
Supervisors, I expect.

00:46:10.680 --> 00:46:12.680
Or the other girls.

00:46:12.680 --> 00:46:14.680
Yeah.

00:46:14.680 --> 00:46:19.680
Were you ever made aware of health and safety then at the time?

00:46:19.680 --> 00:46:26.680
No. Health and safety was nothing until, that's a recent thing.

00:46:26.680 --> 00:46:32.680
What about conditions then? Were the both factories, were they well heated?

00:46:32.680 --> 00:46:36.680
I know some factories were cold in the winter and hot in the summer,

00:46:36.680 --> 00:46:39.680
just because of the nature of the building.

00:46:39.680 --> 00:46:42.680
So what was it like in lotteries?

00:46:42.680 --> 00:46:46.680
It used to get very hot in the summer.

00:46:46.680 --> 00:46:49.680
They used to white out the windows in the roof.

00:46:49.680 --> 00:46:51.680
Was it a new building or an old building?

00:46:51.680 --> 00:46:54.680
It was a new factory unit at the time.

00:46:54.680 --> 00:46:56.680
Oh, right. Yeah.

00:46:56.680 --> 00:46:58.680
I remember you saying now it was a new building.

00:46:58.680 --> 00:47:01.680
It was a big, because they came down from London, you see.

00:47:01.680 --> 00:47:02.680
Yes, yeah.

00:47:02.680 --> 00:47:04.680
They relocated.

00:47:04.680 --> 00:47:06.680
To get cheaper labour possibly.

00:47:06.680 --> 00:47:08.680
That's it.

00:47:08.680 --> 00:47:12.680
We spoke about music last time. We enjoyed that story.

00:47:12.680 --> 00:47:18.680
I was in a military band and it was noisy on the factory floor.

00:47:18.680 --> 00:47:20.680
It was very noisy.

00:47:20.680 --> 00:47:22.680
You didn't mind that though, you got used to it.

00:47:22.680 --> 00:47:26.680
You didn't hear it in the end. The only thing is you couldn't hear.

00:47:26.680 --> 00:47:29.680
It was no good trying to talk to somebody right over there.

00:47:29.680 --> 00:47:31.680
That's why everybody could lip read.

00:47:31.680 --> 00:47:37.680
If you were talking to a woman where that lamp is, you wouldn't be able to hear it really.

00:47:37.680 --> 00:47:40.680
But you couldn't get up and go over. You'd be wasting time.

00:47:40.680 --> 00:47:42.680
Yeah.

00:47:42.680 --> 00:47:46.680
Do you think any girls suffered any long-term effects on their health then?

00:47:46.680 --> 00:47:48.680
Well, I think it affects hearing.

00:47:48.680 --> 00:47:51.680
But they won't pay out.

00:47:51.680 --> 00:47:58.680
We often have these people ringing up saying they were having a hearing test which was job-connected.

00:47:58.680 --> 00:48:01.680
If you worked in a clothing factory, they won't look at you.

00:48:01.680 --> 00:48:02.680
Why not though?

00:48:02.680 --> 00:48:06.680
I don't know. The government won't pay compensation.

00:48:06.680 --> 00:48:08.680
It's because the bill would be too big.

00:48:08.680 --> 00:48:10.680
Yeah.

00:48:10.680 --> 00:48:15.680
And of course as you get older, everybody gets a little bit harder to hear.

00:48:15.680 --> 00:48:17.680
To prove that it was...

00:48:17.680 --> 00:48:22.680
I know we went twice when they ring up now and I say,

00:48:22.680 --> 00:48:28.680
if it's clothing trade, you can forget it.

00:48:28.680 --> 00:48:33.680
And they say, oh yes, you're right, they just won't look at the clothing trade.

00:48:33.680 --> 00:48:35.680
Silly, isn't it?

00:48:35.680 --> 00:48:36.680
Silly, isn't it?

00:48:36.680 --> 00:48:38.680
Because it was a noisy environment.

00:48:38.680 --> 00:48:42.680
Yeah, it's bound to be. And nobody had anything to put over their ears.

00:48:42.680 --> 00:48:45.680
No. Didn't give it a thought, you see.

00:48:45.680 --> 00:48:48.680
Because you didn't actually have to hear.

00:48:48.680 --> 00:48:53.680
After you'd been in a couple of weeks, you could read with the best of them.

00:48:53.680 --> 00:48:55.680
You didn't need anything else.

00:48:55.680 --> 00:49:03.680
Everybody knew that they had to talk and make the mouth shapes.

00:49:03.680 --> 00:49:08.680
And it's amazing how far away you can talk to somebody

00:49:08.680 --> 00:49:12.680
or understand what they're saying if you can lip read.

00:49:12.680 --> 00:49:15.680
Lip read is quite magical,

00:49:15.680 --> 00:49:20.680
but you've got to understand the movement of the mouth.

00:49:20.680 --> 00:49:22.680
Because there's no sound.

00:49:22.680 --> 00:49:26.680
And it's easy. Do lose the knack mind.

00:49:26.680 --> 00:49:27.680
Oh, do you?

00:49:27.680 --> 00:49:28.680
Yeah, I don't think I could do it.

00:49:28.680 --> 00:49:35.680
I still can to a degree, but not as good as you were when you were there doing it all the time.

00:49:35.680 --> 00:49:39.680
But I suppose, oh sorry Mr White, do you want me to stop for a second?

00:49:39.680 --> 00:49:40.680
No, no, no.

00:49:40.680 --> 00:49:43.680
I suppose you get used to lip reading certain people as well, don't you?

00:49:43.680 --> 00:49:44.680
Yeah.

00:49:44.680 --> 00:49:46.680
It might be different with strangers.

00:49:46.680 --> 00:49:48.680
Yeah.

00:49:48.680 --> 00:49:53.680
But you can understand why they can use lip readers on film when they've got no sound.

00:49:53.680 --> 00:49:57.680
And understand what they're saying.

00:49:57.680 --> 00:49:59.680
Because it is quite easy.

00:50:01.680 --> 00:50:04.680
I can't, oh sorry, this one here as well.

00:50:04.680 --> 00:50:07.680
It's lovely, thanks a lot. Thanks.

00:50:09.680 --> 00:50:16.680
So the work in a factory was five days a week with possible extra on Saturdays, is it?

00:50:16.680 --> 00:50:17.680
Sometimes on a Saturday.

00:50:17.680 --> 00:50:23.680
I can't remember because it was a 48-hour week, so I think Saturday was included.

00:50:23.680 --> 00:50:30.680
It was eight till five and eight till one or eight till twelve on a Saturday.

00:50:30.680 --> 00:50:34.680
But was that all the time or was it just when there were particular orders in?

00:50:34.680 --> 00:50:37.680
No, that was a 48-hour week.

00:50:37.680 --> 00:50:38.680
Oh gosh, it's a lot isn't it?

00:50:38.680 --> 00:50:39.680
It's what you worked.

00:50:39.680 --> 00:50:41.680
Most people worked a 48-hour week.

00:50:41.680 --> 00:50:42.680
Oh did they?

00:50:42.680 --> 00:50:43.680
Yeah.

00:50:44.680 --> 00:50:46.680
Then they put it down to 40.

00:50:46.680 --> 00:50:47.680
Yeah.

00:50:47.680 --> 00:50:48.680
And in fact when I worked at the hospital...

00:50:48.680 --> 00:50:51.680
Well at 40 it's a day less isn't it? You know?

00:50:51.680 --> 00:50:52.680
Yeah, it is really.

00:50:52.680 --> 00:50:59.680
And when they put it down to 40 and I started working in the hospital many years later,

00:50:59.680 --> 00:51:07.680
I just assumed that it was a 40-hour week, but I was only working a 47-hour week, a 37-hour week.

00:51:07.680 --> 00:51:08.680
Oh gosh.

00:51:08.680 --> 00:51:11.680
So I always worked 40 hours, I was always there 40 hours.

00:51:11.680 --> 00:51:12.680
Yeah, yeah.

00:51:12.680 --> 00:51:21.680
Because I was used to those sort of hours, 37, you know, and that's sometimes not having a dinner break or anything.

00:51:21.680 --> 00:51:25.680
Was there a...there was a canteen in Lothreys, was there?

00:51:25.680 --> 00:51:26.680
Oh yeah, a lovely canteen.

00:51:26.680 --> 00:51:28.680
So was that subsidised then?

00:51:28.680 --> 00:51:35.680
Yeah, and they did have, also in Lothreys, they had a works council.

00:51:35.680 --> 00:51:40.680
That meant it was very...I think works councils are very progressive.

00:51:40.680 --> 00:51:49.680
They had different girls from different sections of the factory who would stay behind for an evening,

00:51:49.680 --> 00:51:57.680
and they would provide a tea, a substantial tea, and they'd have like a big meeting in the canteen

00:51:57.680 --> 00:52:07.680
where they would discuss all the grievances from their sections with management.

00:52:07.680 --> 00:52:11.680
But were they supervisors or just representatives?

00:52:11.680 --> 00:52:14.680
They were representatives of the factory floor.

00:52:14.680 --> 00:52:16.680
So who would have chosen them then?

00:52:16.680 --> 00:52:17.680
Well, the girls did.

00:52:17.680 --> 00:52:20.680
Oh right, that is very progressive, isn't it?

00:52:20.680 --> 00:52:25.680
And there'd be supervisors there as well, a few. Not all of them, but a few of them.

00:52:25.680 --> 00:52:31.680
And top management would be there. You know, Mr Lothreys himself used to come down for the workers' management.

00:52:31.680 --> 00:52:33.680
So how often would they be held?

00:52:33.680 --> 00:52:35.680
About every three or four months.

00:52:35.680 --> 00:52:40.680
Gosh. So do you remember any decisions being made on the back of these meetings?

00:52:40.680 --> 00:52:44.680
I can't really remember, but I can remember there was a lot of...

00:52:44.680 --> 00:52:52.680
One thing, there was always things like the long queues, not moving fast enough at breaks,

00:52:52.680 --> 00:52:55.680
because you only had a small amount of time.

00:52:55.680 --> 00:53:02.680
So if you wanted a cup of tea, the teas had to be ready when each section went in,

00:53:02.680 --> 00:53:06.680
and you had to be able to pay quickly and sit down and have your tea.

00:53:06.680 --> 00:53:14.680
So that was always a bone of contention, the times that the canteen would keep you waiting out of your break time.

00:53:14.680 --> 00:53:23.680
Then there was problems with toilets, you know, the cleaning of the toilets, all the cloakrooms.

00:53:23.680 --> 00:53:25.680
What, that they weren't clean?

00:53:25.680 --> 00:53:27.680
That they weren't done properly.

00:53:27.680 --> 00:53:35.680
And the complaints about the girls writing on the walls of the toilets. You know, those sort of things.

00:53:35.680 --> 00:53:37.680
But who would be complaining about that?

00:53:37.680 --> 00:53:40.680
The girls. It was quite rude.

00:53:40.680 --> 00:53:43.680
About other girls, or just rude?

00:53:43.680 --> 00:53:47.680
They don't know who did it, you see. Nobody knew who did it.

00:53:47.680 --> 00:53:49.680
They never found out.

00:53:49.680 --> 00:53:53.680
Well, it's another form of expression, isn't it?

00:53:53.680 --> 00:53:56.680
Yeah. You didn't have to read it.

00:53:56.680 --> 00:54:02.680
I suppose it would all depend whether it was about you or not.

00:54:02.680 --> 00:54:09.680
No, they were really rude. Really, really rude.

00:54:09.680 --> 00:54:16.680
Oh dear. Yeah, we were talking about the canteen. The food was good there.

00:54:16.680 --> 00:54:26.680
The food was good, yeah. Never ever complaints about the quality of the food. Just how slow it was being served.

00:54:26.680 --> 00:54:30.680
It's very good psychology to give workers good food though, isn't it?

00:54:30.680 --> 00:54:32.680
It is, yeah.

00:54:32.680 --> 00:54:34.680
It keeps them happy, doesn't it, for a while?

00:54:34.680 --> 00:54:41.680
Oh yeah. You know, when you only got such a little time, a lot of them took their own food in.

00:54:41.680 --> 00:54:43.680
Did you just take your own?

00:54:43.680 --> 00:54:55.680
No. You had to pay for it, but I think that it wasn't extortion, it was reasonable.

00:54:55.680 --> 00:55:00.680
Were the holidays something you were desperate to see coming, you know, having time off?

00:55:00.680 --> 00:55:02.680
You were desperate for time off?

00:55:02.680 --> 00:55:09.680
Well, the clothing trade has closed down fortnight, so you weren't given any choice when you had your holidays.

00:55:09.680 --> 00:55:14.680
And they were always the worst two weeks of the year, because it was the last week of July and the first week of August.

00:55:14.680 --> 00:55:16.680
Worst for weather.

00:55:16.680 --> 00:55:18.680
Yeah, the worst for weather.

00:55:18.680 --> 00:55:20.680
Nothing new there then?

00:55:21.680 --> 00:55:29.680
So unless you went abroad, which you didn't do in those days, no package to earth. I mean, I used to go abroad.

00:55:29.680 --> 00:55:31.680
So where did you go?

00:55:31.680 --> 00:55:38.680
Spain. I went to Holland. And I went to Spain.

00:55:38.680 --> 00:55:51.680
But I wasn't your ordinary everyday Renard Pearson. My cousin worked on the railway. She worked for the railway and the office.

00:55:51.680 --> 00:56:01.680
This is the one, I think I told you, that did sitting girls, dressmaking and design, and then went on and taught.

00:56:01.680 --> 00:56:11.680
But before that she worked for the British Rail in the offices in Newport. And she used to get cheap rail fare, you see.

00:56:11.680 --> 00:56:12.680
That's handy.

00:56:12.680 --> 00:56:18.680
Yeah, she did, but I had to pay full price. So we used to go on holiday together.

00:56:18.680 --> 00:56:19.680
Oh, lovely.

00:56:19.680 --> 00:56:22.680
And my mother would let me go with her, even though I was only fifteen.

00:56:22.680 --> 00:56:27.680
Oh gosh. Well, you wouldn't go abroad when you were fifteen, though, would you?

00:56:27.680 --> 00:56:28.680
Yeah.

00:56:28.680 --> 00:56:29.680
Gosh.

00:56:29.680 --> 00:56:33.680
I went abroad for the first time. But I was with Doreen.

00:56:33.680 --> 00:56:37.680
Before your time. Obviously.

00:56:37.680 --> 00:56:38.680
Yeah.

00:56:38.680 --> 00:56:45.680
The social activities in the factory then, would you socialise much with people outside work?

00:56:45.680 --> 00:56:54.680
No, you didn't have time. You just didn't have time because you were working eight till five by the time you got home.

00:56:54.680 --> 00:57:01.680
We all used to go out together. There was always a Christmas dinner dance where the management all came.

00:57:01.680 --> 00:57:03.680
Was that in the factory?

00:57:03.680 --> 00:57:16.680
No, it was in a hotel, a local hotel. So there was the dinner dance. They used to rent trips during the shutdown for people who didn't go on holiday.

00:57:16.680 --> 00:57:19.680
Did they do it in the shutdown?

00:57:19.680 --> 00:57:24.680
Yeah, they'd have a couple of trips out. They used to go to Western on the paddle steamer.

00:57:24.680 --> 00:57:26.680
But you had to pay for those, presumably?

00:57:26.680 --> 00:57:30.680
Oh yeah. Go to Barry Island on a bus.

00:57:30.680 --> 00:57:33.680
Was there a sports and social club?

00:57:33.680 --> 00:57:34.680
No.

00:57:34.680 --> 00:57:35.680
No.

00:57:35.680 --> 00:57:41.680
But I used to play tennis with two of the fellas in the cutting room.

00:57:42.680 --> 00:57:51.680
We had a tennis court at the back of the factory, adjacent to the canteen. They also used to let me keep the canoe there.

00:57:51.680 --> 00:57:53.680
Canoe?

00:57:53.680 --> 00:58:00.680
Yeah, canoe. My brother and I had a canoe. Of course, we were not far from the river.

00:58:00.680 --> 00:58:02.680
Oh, yes, of course.

00:58:02.680 --> 00:58:09.680
Instead of carting it back and forth on the back of the bike, on a push bike, it's wheeled back and forth.

00:58:09.680 --> 00:58:18.680
There's a long way to go with this canoe. They used to let me keep it in a little room off the canteen.

00:58:20.680 --> 00:58:25.680
I told you I wanted the canoes. I don't want to be every day so...

00:58:25.680 --> 00:58:29.680
Well, at least you didn't take the canoe to go to work.

00:58:29.680 --> 00:58:30.680
No.

00:58:30.680 --> 00:58:34.680
But I used to like playing tennis. I played a lot of tennis.

00:58:34.680 --> 00:58:41.680
Were there any other teams? Were there teams of like... I mean, there were football teams in some factories.

00:58:41.680 --> 00:58:57.680
Yeah, oh no. They weren't that sort of... A lot of them used to cycle to work, but they never did anything with cycling as a sport in things.

00:58:57.680 --> 00:59:16.680
You've told me of a few instances already that you remember. Is there any other event that comes to mind when you think about your work, either at lotteries or at RSW, anybody famous visiting or taking a look at what you're doing or any event?

00:59:16.680 --> 00:59:25.680
No, you always have government inspectors for the army or the British railway.

00:59:25.680 --> 00:59:37.680
But of course they don't do that sort of stuff. There's all those big contracts and are no longer relevant because they don't happen.

00:59:37.680 --> 00:59:51.680
British Railways provided uniforms for their staff. The army staff is made... Well, look, you look at it, if my son was in the army, it's absolute rubbish.

00:59:52.680 --> 01:00:05.680
When he was in Northern Ireland, he did a 12 month first, and then he did something else and they brought him back from Canada when he was in Canada.

01:00:05.680 --> 01:00:14.680
And that was the end. He never could go back. So I don't know what they were doing. And he never told me.

01:00:14.680 --> 01:00:16.680
It was good to keep it a secret then.

01:00:16.680 --> 01:00:26.680
Well, they had to. And they couldn't go back. So what they were doing, I don't know. Because it was dangerous for them to go back. Their faces might have been recognised.

01:00:26.680 --> 01:00:40.680
And he had a body armour and he brought it home with him because he was going to wash it. I said, I'll wash it. But he said, no. He said, I know exactly what to do with it.

01:00:40.680 --> 01:00:51.680
And when I saw it, it was falling apart. I mean, this was body armour. Not like the police wear now. It was absolutely tatty.

01:00:51.680 --> 01:01:03.680
I was disgusted with the quality of it all. Made abroad, you see, somewhere. And it really wanted mending.

01:01:03.680 --> 01:01:11.680
And when he came home on leave, I was always bending those camouflage stuff he had. They were really tatty.

01:01:11.680 --> 01:01:15.680
Oh, were they? You would have thought they'd be hard wearing. They need to be hard wearing.

01:01:15.680 --> 01:01:20.680
They need to be, but they're not. They're not quality fabric.

01:01:20.680 --> 01:01:21.680
Where are they made then?

01:01:21.680 --> 01:01:29.680
I don't know where they're made now. I think they still might be made. Well, I've never heard of anybody making uniform tailoring, doing army stuff.

01:01:29.680 --> 01:01:34.680
There might be factories in London doing it, but I think they're all made abroad.

01:01:34.680 --> 01:01:44.680
Because Gareth, just before he came out, he used to drive warrior personnel carriers.

01:01:45.680 --> 01:01:52.680
He didn't talk a lot, my boy. And he used to go off with his major.

01:01:52.680 --> 01:02:05.680
And before the Iraq War, he went to Iraq with his major, or Jordan or somewhere, where they were having...

01:02:05.680 --> 01:02:10.680
Because you know when our boys went out, they didn't have any light uniforms. They had to go out in...

01:02:10.680 --> 01:02:12.680
Mad, isn't it?

01:02:13.680 --> 01:02:17.680
Well, I think it was criminal. It was really criminal.

01:02:17.680 --> 01:02:32.680
So the people in the War Office wanted to know what sort of uniforms they were wearing, these armies, the Jordanian army and what the uniforms were like.

01:02:32.680 --> 01:02:40.680
And Gareth went with his major on a recce job, looking at and finding out how they manufactured them.

01:02:40.680 --> 01:02:48.680
So I don't think they were manufacturing them in this country. It might have been coming from Sri Lanka or somewhere in India.

01:02:48.680 --> 01:02:56.680
I know the textile factories in West Wales. They went to Morocco, apparently.

01:02:57.680 --> 01:03:08.680
Well, a friend of mine who's got this company in Newport called J&B Builders is a sewing factory. He sells sewing machines.

01:03:08.680 --> 01:03:12.680
He's got three factories in Morocco himself.

01:03:12.680 --> 01:03:14.680
Making garments.

01:03:16.680 --> 01:03:21.680
I think that factories will start coming back here though, eventually.

01:03:21.680 --> 01:03:25.680
Well, the wages will be so low, they can't afford Thailand anymore.

01:03:25.680 --> 01:03:32.680
China, for example. Things are getting more expensive coming from there and they're getting workers' rights now, aren't they?

01:03:32.680 --> 01:03:33.680
Oh, yeah.

01:03:33.680 --> 01:03:42.680
Because I saw something on the telly the other day, and it showed one Chinese person saying, I'm not working for you anymore. I'm going to work for someone else.

01:03:43.680 --> 01:03:50.680
Well, the thing is, Thailand and China are the fastest growing economies in the world.

01:03:50.680 --> 01:03:59.680
And when people want more money, and that's what you say to these girls in the hospital, it's the money you've got to go for.

01:03:59.680 --> 01:04:04.680
Because at the end of the day, that's what benefits your family most, isn't it?

01:04:04.680 --> 01:04:14.680
If you've got to be out working, and most of us can't afford to stay home anymore, you've got to go where you're getting most for your time.

01:04:14.680 --> 01:04:18.680
The time you're away from the family.

01:04:18.680 --> 01:04:20.680
Yeah, it's got to be worthwhile.

01:04:20.680 --> 01:04:25.680
And they get the same. The Japanese and the Chinese used to be Japanese tourists, didn't they?

01:04:25.680 --> 01:04:30.680
But now it's Chinese tourists and Thai tourists.

01:04:30.680 --> 01:04:38.680
And even Vietnam. They've got tourists going all over the place. Vietnamese tourists in London.

01:04:38.680 --> 01:04:41.680
Because they've got the money now to travel.

01:04:41.680 --> 01:04:44.680
Whereas we haven't anymore.

01:04:44.680 --> 01:04:47.680
Stay put, and have a lovely weather.

01:04:47.680 --> 01:04:51.680
Well, the thing is, I think it's affected Spain's economy.

01:04:51.680 --> 01:04:54.680
You know, there's not so many people going to Spain.

01:04:54.680 --> 01:04:57.680
Spain's in a terrible state, isn't it?

01:04:57.680 --> 01:05:07.680
And because of that, the ones that do go, they go long haul now, don't they? Thailand and Vietnam.

01:05:07.680 --> 01:05:11.680
Well, it's cheaper when you actually get there, isn't it? It's quite cheap in places like Vietnam.

01:05:11.680 --> 01:05:14.680
Whereas the flights are so cheaper.

01:05:14.680 --> 01:05:16.680
And the weather is just the same as Spain.

01:05:16.680 --> 01:05:24.680
Spain's got nothing more to offer than Vietnam or Thailand unless you get caught in a tsunami.

01:05:24.680 --> 01:05:26.680
Which happened to a friend of mine.

01:05:26.680 --> 01:05:32.680
She was out there during that terrible tsunami.

01:05:32.680 --> 01:05:38.680
Staying at that pen beach, the one that was absolutely united.

01:05:38.680 --> 01:05:41.680
It took her nearly three years to get over it.

01:05:41.680 --> 01:05:44.680
I'm not surprised. Who was she with?

01:05:44.680 --> 01:05:47.680
She was with her family. They were all alright. They were all in the hotel.

01:05:47.680 --> 01:05:50.680
Which managed to stay standing.

01:05:50.680 --> 01:05:52.680
But did the water come in?

01:05:52.680 --> 01:05:53.680
Yeah.

01:05:53.680 --> 01:05:55.680
Oh, gosh.

01:05:55.680 --> 01:06:01.680
They were on the third floor and the hotel managed to stay standing.

01:06:01.680 --> 01:06:05.680
It was absolutely horrific.

01:06:05.680 --> 01:06:08.680
It was horrific because the kids were there.

01:06:10.680 --> 01:06:15.680
So you know, you pay your men and you take your choice, don't you?

01:06:15.680 --> 01:06:17.680
I don't expect that though, do you?

01:06:17.680 --> 01:06:21.680
No, oh no. That was hopefully a one-off.

01:06:21.680 --> 01:06:23.680
Yeah.

01:06:23.680 --> 01:06:31.680
Just for me to check now, can you remember any dates for when you worked where roughly?

01:06:31.680 --> 01:06:34.680
Just for me to try and pin it down.

01:06:34.680 --> 01:06:38.680
Well, I started work at 15.

01:06:38.680 --> 01:06:43.680
So that's about 1950, 1951.

01:06:43.680 --> 01:06:45.680
And that's at Loutreys.

01:06:45.680 --> 01:06:47.680
That's at Loutreys.

01:06:47.680 --> 01:06:54.680
I worked there for three or four years.

01:06:54.680 --> 01:06:59.680
Then I worked at Western Biscuits for about eight months.

01:06:59.680 --> 01:07:02.680
It wasn't longer than that.

01:07:02.680 --> 01:07:06.680
Then I went back to Loutreys.

01:07:06.680 --> 01:07:10.680
And I stayed there until I was 21.

01:07:10.680 --> 01:07:14.680
22 because I was working there when I got married.

01:07:14.680 --> 01:07:19.680
And I was married in 1958.

01:07:22.680 --> 01:07:31.680
And then I went back again when my daughter was two.

01:07:31.680 --> 01:07:35.680
So in 1960 I was back there again.

01:07:37.680 --> 01:07:41.680
Then I worked there for about another five, four years.

01:07:41.680 --> 01:07:47.680
Then I was working for myself there for a couple of years.

01:07:50.680 --> 01:08:01.680
Then I went to work for Kenny Williams in his other factory in Newport, making stuff for Branson.

01:08:01.680 --> 01:08:04.680
Yeah, but that was self-employed, wasn't it?

01:08:04.680 --> 01:08:06.680
No, I was working for him then.

01:08:06.680 --> 01:08:07.680
Oh, right.

01:08:07.680 --> 01:08:12.680
He had a factory, which he was in partnership with Branson.

01:08:12.680 --> 01:08:15.680
Where was that, did you say?

01:08:15.680 --> 01:08:17.680
That was in Newport again.

01:08:17.680 --> 01:08:18.680
Oh, right, okay.

01:08:18.680 --> 01:08:20.680
But the other side of Newport.

01:08:22.680 --> 01:08:26.680
Then I went up to Harry and worked for him for five years.

01:08:29.680 --> 01:08:31.680
And that was RSW?

01:08:31.680 --> 01:08:35.680
Yeah. Then I worked for myself for two or three years.

01:08:37.680 --> 01:08:39.680
What did I do after that?

01:08:46.680 --> 01:08:55.680
I did lots of things because people always thought that I could do things and they'd offer you a job and they'd keep on to you until you took it.

01:08:55.680 --> 01:08:57.680
It was nice to be in demand.

01:08:57.680 --> 01:09:04.680
Oh, but some of these, you know, they expected you to do, to work miracles.

01:09:05.680 --> 01:09:08.680
And you couldn't always do it because they didn't give you the authority.

01:09:08.680 --> 01:09:09.680
Oh, right.

01:09:13.680 --> 01:09:16.680
What types of jobs were you talking about there?

01:09:16.680 --> 01:09:19.680
I worked for a security firm.

01:09:20.680 --> 01:09:24.680
And the reason I finished with that was because they didn't have a safe.

01:09:24.680 --> 01:09:33.680
And sometimes I was sat in the office on my own with about £200,000 in ammunition boxes,

01:09:33.680 --> 01:09:37.680
and I was sitting in this little cupboard under the stairs.

01:09:37.680 --> 01:09:44.680
And I thought, well, you know, someone's only got to find out about it and it could be nasty.

01:09:44.680 --> 01:09:47.680
I wasn't prepared to do that.

01:09:47.680 --> 01:09:55.680
And what they wanted me to do as well is they were employing a fellow who was a horrible bloke,

01:09:55.680 --> 01:09:57.680
and they wanted to get rid of him.

01:09:57.680 --> 01:10:00.680
And they wanted to find out what he did.

01:10:00.680 --> 01:10:02.680
They didn't know exactly what he did.

01:10:02.680 --> 01:10:09.680
He practically ran the place, but he was crafty, and he was crafty because he used to laugh.

01:10:09.680 --> 01:10:11.680
He wouldn't tell you anything.

01:10:11.680 --> 01:10:13.680
But there's no crime against that.

01:10:13.680 --> 01:10:15.680
There's no law against that, is there?

01:10:15.680 --> 01:10:16.680
No, there's no law against it.

01:10:16.680 --> 01:10:24.680
But really and truly, you come across these people who are afraid to tell you because they're afraid to lose their job.

01:10:24.680 --> 01:10:28.680
They're afraid to give you key information in case you couldn't take their job.

01:10:28.680 --> 01:10:30.680
In that case, that was what I was there for.

01:10:30.680 --> 01:10:33.680
But, you know, they're funny.

01:10:33.680 --> 01:10:35.680
They won't help you at all.

01:10:35.680 --> 01:10:37.680
No information.

01:10:37.680 --> 01:10:39.680
Oh, I see. All right.

01:10:39.680 --> 01:10:40.680
You know, they won't help you.

01:10:40.680 --> 01:10:41.680
In case you...

01:10:41.680 --> 01:10:42.680
He was obstructing your job, see?

01:10:42.680 --> 01:10:43.680
Yes.

01:10:43.680 --> 01:10:44.680
Oh, right, I see.

01:10:44.680 --> 01:10:46.680
Yeah. Oh, no, that's no good, is it?

01:10:46.680 --> 01:10:47.680
No, it's not.

01:10:47.680 --> 01:10:49.680
But it happens all over the place.

01:10:49.680 --> 01:10:54.680
See, he wouldn't help anybody, and they couldn't find out exactly what he...

01:10:54.680 --> 01:10:56.680
They knew what he did, but they didn't know how he did it.

01:10:56.680 --> 01:10:57.680
Oh, I see.

01:10:57.680 --> 01:11:00.680
He was keeping his cards close to his chest.

01:11:00.680 --> 01:11:02.680
Well, they couldn't get rid of him, could they?

01:11:02.680 --> 01:11:03.680
So what happened in the end?

01:11:03.680 --> 01:11:06.680
Well, I got fed up. I told him I didn't want to work there anymore.

01:11:06.680 --> 01:11:07.680
Yeah.

01:11:07.680 --> 01:11:12.680
Because I would be the only person in this place with all that money.

01:11:12.680 --> 01:11:14.680
Yeah. Oh, no, that's no good, is it?

01:11:14.680 --> 01:11:15.680
No.

01:11:16.680 --> 01:11:20.680
What do you think about some of the myths about working in a factory then?

01:11:20.680 --> 01:11:25.680
You know, like the reputation of factory girls sometimes wasn't so good.

01:11:25.680 --> 01:11:27.680
Do you think that's unfair?

01:11:27.680 --> 01:11:28.680
I do think it's unfair.

01:11:28.680 --> 01:11:29.680
Yeah.

01:11:30.680 --> 01:11:32.680
Because it's a job at the end of the day.

01:11:32.680 --> 01:11:33.680
Yeah.

01:11:33.680 --> 01:11:35.680
They've got to work hard for whatever money they get.

01:11:36.680 --> 01:11:40.680
I think it is unfair. Sometimes it is justified, mine.

01:11:40.680 --> 01:11:41.680
Do you think so?

01:11:41.680 --> 01:11:42.680
Yeah, well, yeah.

01:11:43.680 --> 01:11:46.680
I mean, the goings-on were goings-on, you know.

01:11:46.680 --> 01:11:47.680
Yeah.

01:11:48.680 --> 01:11:51.680
A lot of them were no better than they should have been.

01:11:51.680 --> 01:11:53.680
But then that's their choice.

01:11:53.680 --> 01:11:58.680
You know, I can't, you know, just that it gives everybody the same reputation.

01:11:58.680 --> 01:11:59.680
Yeah.

01:12:00.680 --> 01:12:05.680
But there were girls working there who were very talented, weren't there?

01:12:05.680 --> 01:12:09.680
And they haven't really been given credit for what they've done.

01:12:09.680 --> 01:12:11.680
Oh, yeah. And they could have done a lot better for themselves.

01:12:11.680 --> 01:12:12.680
Yeah.

01:12:12.680 --> 01:12:19.680
All of them were capable of, there was a lot of them there who were capable of doing a lot better, with better jobs.

01:12:19.680 --> 01:12:20.680
But the opportunities weren't there.

01:12:20.680 --> 01:12:21.680
No.

01:12:21.680 --> 01:12:25.680
Well, there was plenty of work, but there wasn't a variety of opportunities, I suppose.

01:12:25.680 --> 01:12:30.680
No. It was very difficult to get on if you were female.

01:12:32.680 --> 01:12:35.680
So what were the options apart from factory work?

01:12:35.680 --> 01:12:37.680
Shop work, office work.

01:12:42.680 --> 01:12:48.680
Things like hairdressing, if you wanted that. But those sort of things don't suit everybody today.

01:12:48.680 --> 01:12:49.680
No, they don't.

01:12:49.680 --> 01:12:53.680
And it depends what's available in your location as well, doesn't it?

01:12:53.680 --> 01:12:54.680
Yeah.

01:12:54.680 --> 01:13:01.680
I mean, I've spoken to some girls who dreamed of doing hairdressing, but they lived out in the country, so that's a point.

01:13:01.680 --> 01:13:02.680
Yeah.

01:13:03.680 --> 01:13:05.680
It all depends what's on your doorstep.

01:13:05.680 --> 01:13:06.680
Yeah.

01:13:06.680 --> 01:13:10.680
And just how, I mean, if you were determined you were going to be a hairdresser.

01:13:11.680 --> 01:13:16.680
But there was always something easier to do.

01:13:16.680 --> 01:13:17.680
Yeah.

01:13:17.680 --> 01:13:20.680
So it wasn't worth the struggle.

01:13:20.680 --> 01:13:29.680
So do you think factory work held people back then, in the sense, because it was well-paid work on the doorstep?

01:13:29.680 --> 01:13:30.680
Yep.

01:13:32.680 --> 01:13:35.680
But then a lot of women haven't got a lot of ambition, have they?

01:13:35.680 --> 01:13:45.680
Really and truly, they'd only want to get married, and in those days, within getting married, you're pregnant within the first year, life was settled for you, you know?

01:13:45.680 --> 01:13:46.680
Yeah.

01:13:46.680 --> 01:13:55.680
Because you got married and you had a baby within the year, and sometimes you were already having the baby when you got married, you know?

01:13:55.680 --> 01:13:56.680
Yeah.

01:13:56.680 --> 01:14:03.680
We'd have chairs in the factory that nobody would sit on, because that was the time you became pregnant.

01:14:06.680 --> 01:14:08.680
It was a chair that you didn't sit on.

01:14:10.680 --> 01:14:12.680
It was contagious.

01:14:12.680 --> 01:14:17.680
That was all part of the myth.

01:14:19.680 --> 01:14:25.680
And how would you describe the humour then, in that particular type of workplace?

01:14:25.680 --> 01:14:33.680
Well, I think it's great. There's a lot of camaraderie, you know?

01:14:33.680 --> 01:14:39.680
You'd have a really good laugh, because it'd make the time go, you see?

01:14:39.680 --> 01:14:45.680
I mean, eight hours a day is a lot of hours, nine hours at one time.

01:14:45.680 --> 01:14:47.680
But you were busy for all that time, weren't you?

01:14:47.680 --> 01:14:48.680
Oh, yeah, yeah.

01:14:48.680 --> 01:14:50.680
But you needed something else to keep you going.

01:14:50.680 --> 01:14:52.680
We needed something to occupy your mind, didn't you?

01:14:52.680 --> 01:14:53.680
Yeah.

01:14:53.680 --> 01:14:59.680
That's what I always think about car workers, you see? That was a repetitive, boring thing.

01:14:59.680 --> 01:15:07.680
That's why they were always out on strike for more money. They had too much time on their hands, or too much time on their brains.

01:15:07.680 --> 01:15:14.680
You know, they could sort of go—and you'd get the ones that want to cause trouble, and they'd all be out, wouldn't they?

01:15:14.680 --> 01:15:18.680
And I blamed them for the state that the world is in today.

01:15:20.680 --> 01:15:25.680
And the miners, in a way. I think the miners did themselves a disservice.

01:15:25.680 --> 01:15:27.680
Oh, that was disastrous.

01:15:27.680 --> 01:15:34.680
So why go out for more money? Money was no good to them. The government—so they'd get a big pay rise.

01:15:34.680 --> 01:15:41.680
Go out and try and get a big pay rise. It didn't affect them all. Only a certain few would get the money.

01:15:41.680 --> 01:15:47.680
And what did they do? The government would take half of it off them in tax.

01:15:47.680 --> 01:15:52.680
Well, it was political, wasn't it? It was politically motivated.

01:15:54.680 --> 01:15:58.680
They had aging provocateurs there.

01:15:58.680 --> 01:16:00.680
Yes, they did.

01:16:00.680 --> 01:16:15.680
You see, I always say that if what the miners came out on strike for was six weeks holiday a year paid, and retirement at 55 on a full pension,

01:16:15.680 --> 01:16:21.680
well, that would have been something, hadn't it? Because the only thing that money can do is to buy time.

01:16:21.680 --> 01:16:29.680
It's the only thing on God's earth that buys time. If you've got enough of it, you've got more time.

01:16:29.680 --> 01:16:39.680
But that's what I think about it. You either haven't got any time because you're working all the time, or you've got plenty of time and no money.

01:16:39.680 --> 01:16:44.680
You know? So time is tied up with money.

01:16:44.680 --> 01:16:46.680
Yes, it is.

01:16:46.680 --> 01:16:57.680
And that's what they should have gone for. They'd have had a better life because they'd have had six weeks paid holiday, and they'd have retired at 55 on a full pension.

01:16:57.680 --> 01:17:04.680
That's the things that they should have been going for. Not more money, because the government took half of it.

01:17:04.680 --> 01:17:09.680
I thought it was not very productive.

01:17:09.680 --> 01:17:12.680
Oh, no, it wasn't. It was absolutely destructive.

01:17:12.680 --> 01:17:17.680
Yes. So I do blame them for a lot of the things that went wrong.

01:17:17.680 --> 01:17:26.680
Because if they'd got it, it would have affected the rest of our lives. The rest of us, our lives would have improved.

01:17:26.680 --> 01:17:31.680
Because they'd have had to improve all of our working conditions.

01:17:31.680 --> 01:17:43.680
That's what I always felt. And especially the car workers, because they were in good. And what good to them. I mean, their industry is in turmoil, isn't it?

01:17:43.680 --> 01:17:45.680
It's gone basically, isn't it?

01:17:45.680 --> 01:17:46.680
Yes.

01:17:46.680 --> 01:18:02.680
Because it's gone somewhere else. So they should have been going out for more holidays, paid early retirement. And they'd have benefited. I think they were men who were really stupid.

01:18:02.680 --> 01:18:09.680
I think you're right there. Patricia, that's it. Thank you very, very much. It's been fantastic. Thank you.

